### Describe the bug

I set the `ASPNETCORE_URLS` value in `.env` to `https://redacted.azurewebsites.net`. When I clicked on `Fetch data`, I expected the request to be proxied to `https://redacted.azurewebsites.net/weatherforecast`. Instead I get a 404. 

When I run Fiddler, I don't see any attempt to contact the remote server.

I also tried changing `.env.development`.

### To Reproduce

1. Create an ASP.NET Core + React application using the built-in templates
2. Deploy the services to a server (e.g. Azure)
3. Open `.env` and set `ASPNETCORE_URLS` to the server in step 2.
4. Run just the client using `npm start`.

### Exceptions (if any)
404

### Further technical details
- ASP.NET Core version: .NET 6
- The IDE (VS / VS Code/ VS4Mac) you're running on, and its version: Command line.

Code from template: `ClientApp\src\setupProxy.js`

```
const createProxyMiddleware = require('http-proxy-middleware');
const { env } = require('process');

const target = env.ASPNETCORE_HTTPS_PORT ? `https://localhost:${env.ASPNETCORE_HTTPS_PORT}` :
  env.ASPNETCORE_URLS ? env.ASPNETCORE_URLS.split(';')[0] : 'http://localhost:12107';

const context =  [
  "/weatherforecast",
];

module.exports = function(app) {
  const appProxy = createProxyMiddleware(context, {
    target: target,
    secure: false
  });

  app.use(appProxy);
};
```

